SIMPLE: grommet
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: grommet
<hw>grom"met</hw> <pr>(gr⟦ocr⟧m"m⟦ecr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>gourmette</ets> curb, curb chain, fr. <ets>gourmer</ets> to curb,
thump, beat; cf. Armor. <ets>gromm</ets> a curb, <ets>gromma</ets> to
curb.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A ring formed by twisting on itself a
single strand of an unlaid rope. Sometimes written
<asp>grummet</asp>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any eyelet or ring of metal or other material
inserted in a hole in a sheet of some other material; in sailing, a
metallic ring in or for a sail or a mailbag.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A ring of rubber or other insulating material
inserted in a hole in some surface of a device, to prevent wires passing
through the hole from making contact with the surface; used especially
in electrical and electronic devices, to prevent undesired electrical
contact.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A ring of rope used as a wad to
hold a cannon ball in place.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gromwell</ent>⟦br⟧
